## 5. Recommendations for Improving Medicaid Cost-Effectiveness

Based on the evidence and examples presented, the following recommendations are proposed:

| Recommendation | Description | Expected Impact |
|----------------|-------------|-----------------|
| Expand coverage of evidence-based preventive services | Fully cover tobacco cessation, asthma management, contraceptive services, and diabetes prevention programs with minimal barriers | Improved health outcomes; reduced costly complications |
| Implement bundled payment models for high-cost episodes | Adopt prospective or retrospective bundled payments for conditions like joint replacement, maternity care, and chronic disease management | Reduced fragmentation; cost savings; improved care coordination |
| Foster Medicaid-Medicare alignment | Align payment reforms and care models across Medicaid and Medicare to reduce administrative burden and improve care for dual eligibles | Increased efficiency; better care continuity |
| Invest in HIT and care coordination infrastructure | Promote EHR adoption, regional HIEs, and care coordination teams | Enhanced data sharing; reduced duplication; improved quality |
| Remove administrative barriers | Eliminate copays, prior authorizations, and restrictive policies that limit access to effective treatments | Increased utilization of beneficial services; better adherence |
| Support provider education and engagement | Train providers on evidence-based guidelines and value-based care models | Improved clinical practice; increased provider buy-in |

---

## Conclusion

Improving Medicaid while delivering cost-effectiveness requires a multifaceted approach that combines evidence-based clinical interventions, innovative payment reforms, delivery system integration, and robust health information technology. The CDC’s 6|18 Initiative provides a valuable framework targeting high-burden conditions with proven strategies. Payment reforms such as bundled payments and ACOs align incentives to promote value over volume. Integration of care and HIT facilitate coordination and reduce waste.

State-level experiences, such as those in South Carolina and New York, demonstrate the feasibility and benefits of these approaches. Policymakers should prioritize expanding coverage of preventive services, adopting alternative payment models, aligning Medicaid and Medicare reforms, and investing in infrastructure and education to achieve sustainable improvements in Medicaid.

